    "source": "_Overview_of_Sake_and_Distilled_Spirits_with_Addit",
    "contenu": "The document provided is an educational piece on beverages, focusing on wine, beer, and distilled spirits, extracted from a page numbered 758. The content is divided into sections discussing \"Sake\" and \"Distilled Spirits\", along with additional information on \"Japanese Cooking Alcohols: Mirin and Sake Lees\". Here is a structured analysis of the key information from the text:\n\n### Sake\n- **Characteristics**: Sake has a less tart and more diacetylly flavored profile than wine. Its aroma can vary significantly depending on production methods, involving complex biochemistry of yeasts.\n- **Fragility**: Sake is delicate and vulnerable to alteration by exposure to both light and high temperatures. It is recommended to be consumed young and stored in cool, dark places.\n- **Consumption Advice**: Once opened, it should be consumed quickly due to its fragility when exposed to air.\n\n### Distilled Spirits\n- **Basic Concept**: Distilled spirits are derived from the essence of wine and beer. They involve heating a mixture where substances boil at different temperatures, capturing the alcohol in the vapor through condensation.\n- **Boiling Point**: Alcohol boils at 173°F (78°C), and the resultant vapors are then cooled and condensed back into liquid form.\n\n### The History of Distilled Spirits\n- **Origin of Distillation**: The process, historically used to concentrate essential oils, is traced back to Mesopotamians. The discovery exploited the inability of brewing yeasts to tolerate high alcohol concentrations, emphasizing distillation as a method of enhancing the alcoholic content of beverages.\n\n### Japanese Cooking Alcohols: Mirin and Sake Lees\n- **Mirin**: A sweet cooking alcohol combined from cooked polished rice, koji, and shochu. This results in a full-bodied liquid with about 14% alcohol content after a fermentation that inhibits further alcoholic development.\n- **Sake Lees (Sake Kasu)**: The residue from pressing the sake mash, rich in starch, proteins, and enzymes. It is extensively used in Japanese cooking, notably for making vegetable pickles and marinades for fish and soups.\n\n**Analytical Comments**:\nThe document emphasizes the chemistry, production methods, and cultural usage of these beverages, providing a condensed but detailed insight into the sophisticated nature of sake and distilled spirits."
