    "contenu": "Here is the structured content extracted from the document:\n\n---\n\n**Dark Chocolate and Grenache Pairing**\n\nDark chocolate has a perfect companion in robust wines like Banyuls, Maury, or Rasteau. While not as sweet as port, these Grenache-based fortified wines excel with chocolate, offering complementary tastes that might include hints of raisins, citrus, or dark cherries. These wines also pair beautifully with baked figs.\n\n**Pairing Pointers for Grenache**\n\nGrenache pairs well with:\n- **Al fresco dining**: Light options like a crisp rosé or a light Côtes du Rhône with cold roasts, mixed cold cuts, sandwiches, potato salad, coleslaw, and grilled items.\n- **Seafood**: Simple dishes like shellfish prepared with boldly flavored oils or garlic stand out with Grenache rosé.\n- **Hearty dishes**: Rich Grenache blends complement lamb dishes, stews, and even spicy foods like peppery Syrah blends.\n- **Cheese**: This wine goes well with lightly aged or semi-hard cheeses; its versatility handles both the light and robust flavors well.\n- **Chocolate desserts**: Fortified Grenache like Banyuls enhances desserts such as chocolate mousse or macaroons drizzled with chocolate.\n\n**When Grenache Isn’t Ideal**\n\n- **Age-sensitive**: Most Grenache wines are best enjoyed young; they generally do not age well, losing their vibrance and tannins that can block flavors.\n- **Certain seafood**: Raw oysters and clams may clash with the wine's potency, turning the taste sour—however, cooked preparations can be delightful.\n\n--- \n\nThe structured breakdown provides an overview of appropriate and less ideal pairings for Grenache, focusing on the range of dishes that can either enhance or be diminished by this type of wine."
  },
